                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>“perish quickly, <add>?</add>!” To <hi rend=\"underline\">me</hi> should these<lb/>\n                consoling words be uttered rather<lb/> than to <hi rend=\"underline\">you</hi>. For\n                have you not withstood<lb/> all these throes of time and fate?<lb/> Have you not\n                tasted the bitter cup<lb/> and yet survived its draught, to live<lb/> a life more\n                blessed? Heaven hath<lb/> been with you still, and your heart is<lb/> yet ambient in\n                its effulgent love for<lb/> the noble cause espoused five and<lb/> twenty years ago.\n                And though it<lb/> be as <persName>Byron</persName> hath it—</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">“Years still fire from the brain<lb/> As vigor from the limb<lb/>\n                And life's enchanted cup<lb/> But sparkles near the brim”<lb/> Yet to age there\n                comes no “chilling<lb/> frost” if the heart be warm and<lb/> the spirit steadfast.\n                There is “a<lb/> green youth in age” that makes of<lb/> it a holy and a blessed\n                time.<lb/> Please Heaven such be thine for<lb/> eye! Xxx I have sent the recp<lb/>\n                to <persName>Miss L &amp; W</persName>. I will take the</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3mw2914d/canvas/p3"
                }
              ]
